380	After Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule_prime} the cohomology-of-an-open carriers $\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,X$ are well-defined and carry the canonical $\Module k$-structure inherited from \lstinline{Abelian.Ext.instModule} through the \lstinline{noncomputable abbrev} reducibility. The natural follow-on companion, mirroring iter-010's $H^0$ bridge for the parallel $\HModule$ (Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule_zero_linearEquiv}), is the identification of the degree-zero piece $\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,0\,X$ with a Hom group: this is the algebraic prerequisite that downstream Stein-factorization-derived $H^0(C, \struct C) \simeq k$ arguments on a connected proper $k$-curve will eventually consume.
381	
382	The Lean implementation reuses Mathlib's \lstinline{CategoryTheory.Abelian.Ext.linearEquiv₀} (file \lstinline{Mathlib/Algebra/Homology/DerivedCategory/Ext/Linear.lean}), specialised to the $\Linear k$-enriched abelian category $\Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat\,k)$ (the $\Linear k$ enrichment is auto-inferable from \lstinline{HasSheafify} via \lstinline{Sheaf.linear}).
383	
384	\begin{definition}[$H^0$ as a $k$-linear Hom group, $\HModulePrime$ flavor]
385	  \label{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_zero_linearEquiv}
386	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule'_zero_linearEquiv}
387	  \leanok
388	  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule_prime, thm:HasSheafify_Opens_ModuleCatK, thm:HasExt_Sheaf_Opens_ModuleCatK}
389	  Let $k$ be a field, $(C, J)$ a Grothendieck site with $\HasWeakSheafify\,J\,(\mathrm{Type}\,u)$, $\HasSheafify\,J\,(\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k)$, and $\HasExt(\Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k))$, $X : C$, and $F : \Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k)$. Then there is a canonical $k$-linear equivalence
390	  \[
391	    \mathtt{HModulePrime\_zero\_linearEquiv}_X \,:\, \HModulePrime\,k\,F\,0\,X \;\simeq_k\; \bigl((\mathtt{presheafToSheaf}\,J\,(\ModuleCat\,k)).\mathrm{obj}\,((\yoneda \circ \free_k).\mathrm{obj}\,X) \,\to\, F\bigr)
392	  \]
393	  given by \lstinline{Abelian.Ext.linearEquiv₀}.
394	\end{definition}
395	
396	\begin{proof}
397	  \leanok
398	  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule_prime}
399	  Direct from \lstinline{CategoryTheory.Abelian.Ext.linearEquiv₀} applied to the abelian category $\Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat\,k)$, which is $\Linear k$-enriched (auto-inferable from the prerequisites of Section~\ref{sec:moduleK_prereqs}) and has $\HasExt$ (Theorem~\ref{thm:HasExt_Sheaf_Opens_ModuleCatK}). The $\noncomputable$ \lstinline{abbrev} reducibility of $\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,0\,X$ (Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule_prime}) lets instance synthesis unfold the wrapper to the underlying $\Ext^0$ group, and \lstinline{linearEquiv₀} returns the $\Module k$-linear bijection between that $\Ext^0$ group and the corresponding Hom group in the sheaf category. The closure body is therefore a one-liner \lstinline{Abelian.Ext.linearEquiv₀}; iter-015 plan-agent \lstinline{lean_run_code} probe confirms the closure compiles end-to-end against current Mathlib + project state, kernel-only axioms.
400	\end{proof}
401	
402	\begin{remark}[Choice of \texttt{def} over \texttt{abbrev}]
403	  Unlike $\HModulePrime$ itself (which uses \lstinline{noncomputable abbrev} to keep the wrapper reducible for instance synthesis on the underlying $\Ext$ group), the $H^0$-bridge auxiliary uses \lstinline{noncomputable def}. Reason: the result is a $\simeq_k$ between two known types whose $\Module\,k$ and $\AddCommGroup$ instances are already inferable through the iter-014 \lstinline{HModule'} reducibility; a \lstinline{def} form is fine, and \lstinline{abbrev} would over-expose the body without additional benefit. This mirrors iter-010's choice for the parallel $\HModule\_zero\_linearEquiv$ (Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule_zero_linearEquiv}).
404	\end{remark}
405	
406	\begin{remark}[Why this completes the Mayer-Vietoris algebraic prerequisites]
407	  Mathlib's Mayer-Vietoris LES for an abelian sheaf in \lstinline{AddCommGrpCat}-flavor uses both $\Sheaf.\HPrime\,n\,X$ (the cohomology-of-an-open carrier) \emph{and} the $H^0$ identification with global sections (the spliced-in zeroth term). On the $\ModuleCat\,k$ side, the iter-014 $\HModulePrime$ provides the carrier and the iter-015 \lstinline{HModule'_zero_linearEquiv} provides the $H^0$ identification: together they are the algebraic preliminaries. The substantive Mayer-Vietoris LES theorem itself (mirroring \lstinline{Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Sites/SheafCohomology/MayerVietoris.lean} line-by-line for the $\ModuleCat\,k$-flavored carriers) is queued for iter-016+.
408	\end{remark}
409	
410	\section{$\Module\,k$-finite transport companions for the $H^0$ bridges (iter-038)}
411	\label{sec:HModule_finite_zero_iter038}
412	
413	After Definitions~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule_zero_linearEquiv} and~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_zero_linearEquiv} the iteration~010/015 $H^0$ bridges identify $\HModule\,k\,F\,0$ and $\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,0\,X$ with $k$-linear Hom groups. The iteration~038 companions package the immediate $\Module\,k$-finite transport: from finiteness of the Hom group, finiteness of the cohomology group follows by Mathlib's \lstinline{Module.Finite.equiv} (\lstinline{Mathlib/RingTheory/Finiteness/Basic.lean}). They mirror iteration~037's \lstinline{module_finite_HModule_of_HModule'_X₄} pattern (which performs the analogous transport across the iteration~035 corner-bridge, at general degree $n$ rather than degree $0$).
414	
415	\begin{theorem}\leanok
416	[$\Module\,k$-finite transport for $\HModule\,k\,F\,0$]
417	  \label{thm:Scheme_module_finite_HModule_zero}
418	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.module_finite_HModule_zero}
419	  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule_zero_linearEquiv}
420	  Let $k$ be a field, $C$ a small category, $J$ a Grothendieck topology on $C$ with $\HasSheafify\,J\,(\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k)$ and $\HasExt(\Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k))$. For $F : \Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k)$ such that the $k$-linear Hom group $((\mathtt{constantSheaf}\,J\,(\ModuleCat\,k)).\mathrm{obj}\,(\ModuleCat.\mathrm{of}\,k\,k) \to F)$ is $\Module.\mathrm{Finite}$ over $k$, the cohomology group $\HModule\,k\,F\,0$ is also $\Module.\mathrm{Finite}$ over $k$.
421	\end{theorem}
422	
423	\begin{proof}
424	  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule_zero_linearEquiv}
425	  \leanok
426	  Direct application of \lstinline{Module.Finite.equiv} to the symmetric form of the iteration~010 $H^0$ bridge. Mathlib's \lstinline{Module.Finite.equiv} consumes a $k$-linear equivalence $M \simeq_k N$ together with $[\Module.\mathrm{Finite}\,k\,M]$ and produces $[\Module.\mathrm{Finite}\,k\,N]$. Applied to $(\mathtt{HModule\_zero\_linearEquiv}\,k\,F).\mathtt{symm} : ((\mathtt{constantSheaf}\,J\,\_).\mathrm{obj}\,(\ModuleCat.\mathrm{of}\,k\,k) \to F) \simeq_k \HModule\,k\,F\,0$, the Hom-group hypothesis on the LHS transports to the cohomology-group conclusion on the RHS. One-liner term-mode body \lstinline{Module.Finite.equiv (HModule_zero_linearEquiv k F).symm}.
427	\end{proof}
428	
429	\begin{theorem}\leanok
430	[$\Module\,k$-finite transport for $\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,0\,X$]
431	  \label{thm:Scheme_module_finite_HModule_prime_zero}
432	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.module_finite_HModule'_zero}
433	  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_zero_linearEquiv}
434	  Let $k$ be a field, $C$ a small category, $J$ a Grothendieck topology on $C$ with $\HasWeakSheafify\,J\,(\mathrm{Type}\,u)$, $\HasSheafify\,J\,(\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k)$, and $\HasExt(\Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k))$. For $F : \Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k)$ and $X : C$ such that the $k$-linear Hom group $((\mathtt{presheafToSheaf}\,J\,\_).\mathrm{obj}\,((\yoneda \circ \free_k).\mathrm{obj}\,X) \to F)$ is $\Module.\mathrm{Finite}$ over $k$, the cohomology group $\HModulePrime\,k\,F\,0\,X$ is also $\Module.\mathrm{Finite}$ over $k$.
435	\end{theorem}
436	
437	\begin{proof}
438	  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_zero_linearEquiv}
439	  \leanok
440	  Direct application of \lstinline{Module.Finite.equiv} to $(\mathtt{HModulePrime\_zero\_linearEquiv}\,k\,F\,X).\mathtt{symm}$, parallel to Theorem~\ref{thm:Scheme_module_finite_HModule_zero}. One-liner term-mode body \lstinline{Module.Finite.equiv (HModule'_zero_linearEquiv k F X).symm}.
441	\end{proof}
442	
443	\begin{remark}[Use in Serre finiteness]
444	  Together with iteration~037's \lstinline{module_finite_HModule_of_HModule'_X₄} (the analogue at general degree $n$ via the corner-bridge), the project now has the complete algebraic-to-cohomological $\Module.\mathrm{Finite}$ transport infrastructure at degree $0$ (no Mayer-Vietoris LES required) and at any degree via the corner-bridge (Mayer-Vietoris LES required for the geometric inputs). The substantive geometric inputs (Serre vanishing on affines, finiteness of the Hom-from-constant-sheaf for proper schemes) remain queued for iter-039+.
445	\end{remark}
446	
447	\section{Use in the project}
448	
449	The composition of the four typeclass instances of Sections~\ref{sec:moduleK_prereqs}–\ref{sec:moduleK_ext}, Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_toModuleKSheaf}, and Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule} delivers Phase~A step~5 in full and bridges to Phase~A step~6:
450	
451	\begin{itemize}
452	  \item For $C : \Over\,(\Spec\,(\CommRingCat\,k))$, the $\ModuleCat\,k$-flavoured cohomology
453	    \[
454	      H^n_{\Module\,k}(C, \struct C) \;:=\; \mathtt{HModule}\,k\,(\toModuleKSheaf\,C)\,n
455	    \]
456	    is well-defined and automatically carries a $\Module\,k$ instance, so $\Module.\mathtt{finrank}\,k\,(\HModule\,k\,(\toModuleKSheaf\,C)\,1) : \mathbb N$ is well-defined.
457	  \item The forgetful functor $\ModuleCat\,k \to \AddCommGrpCat$ recovers the iter-004 abelian-group cohomology (Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_toModuleKSheaf_forgetCompare}), so the new $\HModule$ commutes with the existing $\Sheaf.\mathtt H$ on the underlying type level.
458	  \item Phase~A step~6 (Serre finiteness, $\finrank_k H^i(C, \mathcal F) < \infty$) remains the deep work to come, but is now expressible inside Mathlib's standard $\Module\,k$ API: the statement of Serre finiteness becomes a $\Module.\mathtt{Finite}\,k\,(\HModule\,k\,F\,n)$ predicate.
459	\end{itemize}
460	
461	\section{Mathlib gap}
462	
463	After Section~\ref{sec:scheme_toModuleKSheaf} is implemented, this chapter has no remaining Mathlib gap. The construction reuses only the following established Mathlib pieces:
464	
465	\begin{itemize}
466	  \item \lstinline{CategoryTheory.HasSheafify}, \lstinline{CategoryTheory.HasExt.standard}, and the abelian/$\Linear\,k$ enrichment on $\Sheaf(J, \ModuleCat\,k)$ (verified by \texttt{lean\_run\_code} probes; underlies Sections~\ref{sec:moduleK_prereqs}–\ref{sec:moduleK_ext}).
467	  \item \lstinline{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.\Gamma SpecIso}, \lstinline{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.Hom.app}, \lstinline{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.presheaf} (existing Mathlib API for the structure morphism and the structure-sheaf restriction maps).
468	  \item \lstinline{Algebra.compHom} / \lstinline{RingHom.toAlgebra} (algebra-from-ring-map).
469	  \item \lstinline{CategoryTheory.Presheaf.isSheaf_iff_isSheaf_forget} (concrete-category sheaf criterion; transfers the sheaf condition between $\CommRingCat$ and $\ModuleCat\,k$).
470	\end{itemize}
471	
472	Nothing genuinely new is required from Mathlib. The iter-006 plan-agent \texttt{lean\_run\_code} probe verifies the full $\sim$80-LOC construction end-to-end against Mathlib \texttt{b80f227}.
